When using berry jams why not make them like they did traditionally in Sweden, mix with water rather than sugar or even simpler smash up the berries with a fork or blender and simply serve - all the natural goodness with no added sugar! #sugar #healthyliving #nutritiontips

OME Health’s Football World Cup – Team #27 Sweden. Lingonberries go with anything in Sweden, whether it’s with their famous meatballs or pancakes! Many Swedes grow up picking lingonberries in the forest and using these red fruits to make a jam-like preserve. pic.twitter.com/6wUshHn8hN

OME Health’s Football World Cup – Team #24 Costa Rica. Gallo pinto consists of rice mixed with red or black beans and often some vegetables too. Be inspired and mix up your side of rice for this! A great way to increase fibre and plant-based protein to your diet. pic.twitter.com/sZHkiT6Pyc

Making your own versions of your favourite meals at home allows you to be in charge of what’s added and what’s excluded! #fakeaway #nutritiontips

OME Health’s Football World Cup – Team #22 Uruguay. Chivito is a dish commonly enjoyed in Uruguay, like a glorified burger it may not be the healthiest of foods there's always healthy ways to adjust meals! #uruguay #URUFRA pic.twitter.com/61vF8omsoS

OME Health’s Football World Cup – Team #20 Saudi Arabia. Kabsa: a mixed rice which includes a range of spices, including saffron. Saffron is suggested to benefit your mental health, although research is limited there's no harm in adding it to your food to enjoy! pic.twitter.com/Wnd4irxXu6

OME Health’s Football World Cup – Team #19 Senegal. Thieboudienneis the national dish of Senegal. It includes flavoursome fish, marinated in parsley, lemon, garlic, onion and other herbs too. If you're trying to lower your salt intake, flavour with herbs instead! pic.twitter.com/ECkp1N2XA2

Include rolled oats, almonds, coconut flakes, pecans, walnuts, chia seeds and fresh and dried fruit. Pair it with milk or yoghurt of your choice - we love kefir! Instead of adding sugar add cinnamon, nutmeg or ginger and you’re good to go! #healthyrecipes

OME Health’s Football World Cup - Team #18 Switzerland. Birchermüseli was originally made by a Swiss physician but is now a popular breakfast in Switzerland and lots of Europe. However prepackaged muesli can be seriously high in sugar so try making your own! pic.twitter.com/uruImVrjY7

OME Health’s Football World Cup – Team #17 Japan. Japan is home to some of the healthiest people on the planet, and it's probably all thanks to their diet. High in colourful veg, unrefined grains, fish, green tea, fermented foods & low in sugar. #japan #JAPvBEL pic.twitter.com/rDkjP0kRjy

OME Health’s Football World Cup – Team #16 Peru. In Peru ceviche is considered their national dish & is made of chunks of raw fish, marinated in freshly squeezed lime/lemon with sliced onions & chilli peppers. There is even a national holiday in Peru for ceviche! pic.twitter.com/HfDYEEJpuH

OME Health’s Football World Cup – Team #15 Egypt. Ful mudammas and Ta’meya (Fava Beas and Falafel) are the original Egyptian fast food. The ta’meya, or Egyptian falafel is made from crushed fava beans (different to lebenese falafel made from chickpeas). #fifa #food pic.twitter.com/dsCfnlHDVO

OME Health’s Football World Cup – Team #13 Australia. Kangaroo meat, maybe not an Australian staple, but these 'alternative' red meats are becoming more popular. Are they better? Nutritionally-wise maybe, but we should still be careful of our red meat consumption. pic.twitter.com/VzpbuC4oF8

OME Health’s Football World Cup – Team #12 Colombia. Bandeja paisa is a Colombian national dish containing a whole array of foods making it really nutritionally balanced. Plantain is particularly great; a less-sweet relative of the banana, providing complex carbs. pic.twitter.com/djFTjcCn4M

Try including more cruciferous veg in your diet! Try cauliflower, cabbage, kale, spinach, Brussels sprouts, bok choy or any other similar green leafy vegetables #health #cruciferousveg #phytochemicals
